t3900.text: One is mad; the other is glad – same event, totally contrasting emotions. One is a golfer; the other is a gardener. The golfer in the rain says, “My game is going to be spoiled.” He is mad. The gardener in the rain says, “My plants are going to grow” and he is glad.

t3901.text: There is A–the activating event, B–a belief about the event, C–the consequent emotion. You don’t go from the activating event (A) to (C), the consequent emotion. You get to the emotion by going through what you believe about the event. Eg. Two men are caught in a rainstorm. ...

t3902.text: The most important thing about your events is not the event themselves; it’s what you believe about them. And the #belief will produce the #emotion and the emotion will produce the #behavior. Albert Ellis, a psychologist on the ABC of our emotions. ...
